</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9736CD2E103E55A5D09E03AEF38BB1" blockId="11.[498,1516,1083,1191]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
<taxonomicName id="4C284D4E2E103E55A5D09E03AED68B68" authority="Castello-Branco &amp; Collins &amp; Hajdu, 2020" authorityName="Castello-Branco &amp; Collins &amp; Hajdu" authorityYear="2020" box="[498,687,1124,1150]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Euplectellidae" genus="Bolosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lyssacinosida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="perezi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A5D09E03AED68B68" box="[498,687,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Bolosoma perezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A26F57A42E103E55A6959E04AF6A8B68" box="[695,787,1123,1150]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is the only 
<taxonomicName id="4C284D4E2E103E55A7BD9E03A8768B68" authorityName="Ijima" authorityYear="1904" box="[927,1039,1124,1150]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Euplectellidae" genus="Bolosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lyssacinosida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A7BD9E03A8768B68" box="[927,1039,1124,1150]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Bolosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
with discohexasters and codonhexasters microscleres.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33265462E103E55A5D09EAEAEF789A5" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B9736CD2E103E55A5D09EAEAF828A23" blockId="11.[498,1542,1225,1333]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
EXTERNAL MORPHOLOGY. Sponge fragment, cushion-shaped and compressible, 162 mm in length × 78 mm in width × 16–27 mm in height; fragment apparently without a peduncle, color light gray in ethanol (
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A7939F7DAFB98A22" bold="true" box="[945,960,1306,1332]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">fi</emphasis>
g. 6).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9736CD2E103E55A5D09F3EAEF789A5" blockId="11.[498,1542,1368,1715]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
SKELETON AND SPICULES. A few long cemented diactins (40–80 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A1089F3EA9438A65" bold="true" box="[1322,1338,1369,1395]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">m</emphasis>
m diameter and over 900 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A6419FE7AE0A8A8C" bold="true" box="[611,627,1408,1434]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">m</emphasis>
m long), which we assume are fragments of a peduncle. Choanosomal diactins with rough ends and rudiments of tangential rays (1,275–3,125 × 5–8 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A18E9FCFA9C58AD4" bold="true" box="[1452,1468,1448,1474]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">m</emphasis>
m). Dermal and atrial hexactins and rare atrial pentactins with rough ends and sometimes random spines along the ray (270‒830 × 5‒8 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A0BA9F9FA8D18904" bold="true" box="[1176,1192,1528,1554]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">m</emphasis>
m). Microscleres are ball-like discohexasters (70‒80 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A7239C47AF68892C" bold="true" box="[769,785,1568,1594]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">m</emphasis>
m diameter), its derivates (stauractins, 42–50 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A11E9C47A935892C" bold="true" box="[1340,1356,1568,1594]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">m</emphasis>
m diameter), and codonhexasters (155–175 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A7409C2FAF0B8974" bold="true" box="[866,882,1608,1634]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">m</emphasis>
m diameter, primary rosettes 27–43 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A10E9C2FA9458974" bold="true" box="[1324,1340,1608,1634]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">m</emphasis>
m diameter). The last one with six primary rays and secondary rays in number of four; discs with nine teeth (
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A6639CF0AE2889A7" bold="true" box="[577,593,1687,1713]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">fi</emphasis>
g. 7).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33265462E103E55A5D09CB1AE8F8857" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B9736CD2E103E55A5D09CB1AE8F8857" blockId="11.[498,1542,1749,1857]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">
DISTRIBUTION AND ECOLOGY. Known only from its type locality in the Rio Grande Rise (Southwest Atlantic), 1,022–1,013 m depth. This is the 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A0839C99A8C9880E" bold="true" box="[1185,1200,1790,1816]" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">fi</emphasis>
rst record of 
<taxonomicName id="4C284D4E2E103E55A1619C99A9CA880E" authorityName="Ijima" authorityYear="1904" box="[1347,1459,1790,1816]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Euplectellidae" genus="Bolosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lyssacinosida" pageId="11" pageNumber="12" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E103E55A1619C99A9CA880E" box="[1347,1459,1790,1816]" italics="true" pageId="11" pageNumber="12">Bolosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the entire Atlantic Ocean.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33265462E173E52A5D09A8DA8498E42" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B9736CD2E173E52A5D09A8DA8498E42" blockId="12.[498,1542,233,341]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
ETYMOLOGY. The speci 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E173E52A7039A8DAF498E12" bold="true" box="[801,816,234,260]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">fi</emphasis>
c epithet honors Prof. Dr. Angel Perez (UNIVALI, Brazil) for granting us access to Rio Grande Rise materials, and for our long-standing collaboration in the study of South Atlantic deep-sea ecosystems.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C33265462E173E52A5D09B1EA9838D4D" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B9736CD2E173E52A5D09B1EAE218E82" blockId="12.[498,1541,377,603]" box="[498,600,377,404]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<heading id="D0DF81A12E173E52A5D09B1EAE218E82" bold="true" box="[498,600,377,404]" fontSize="11" level="3" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" reason="0">Remarks</heading>
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B9736CD2E173E52A5D09BC6A9838D4D" blockId="12.[498,1541,377,603]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">
<taxonomicName id="4C284D4E2E173E52A5D09BC6AE248EAD" authorityName="Ijima" authorityYear="1904" box="[498,605,417,443]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Euplectellidae" genus="Bolosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lyssacinosida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E173E52A5D09BC6AE248EAD" box="[498,605,417,443]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Bolosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
comprises eight species (see comparative 
<tableCitation id="C6AA03762E173E52A00B9BC6A8038EAA" box="[1065,1146,417,444]" captionStart="Table 1" captionStartId="13.[208,263,452,474]" captionTargetBox="[199,1861,523,1836]" captionText="Table 1 Comparative data for habit, anatomy, spicules and occurrence for Bolosoma spp. Data for new species presently generated. Data for previously known species gathered from the literature. All morphometric data are in micrometers (µm). n.o., not observed." httpUri="http://table.plazi.org/id/DF5766452E163E53A4F29BA3A8028EE0" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" tableUuid="DF5766452E163E53A4F29BA3A8028EE0">Table 1</tableCitation>
), up to now recorded only from the Paci 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E173E52A6039BAFAE498EF4" bold="true" box="[545,560,456,482]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">fi</emphasis>
c Ocean. The new species presents a unique set of spicules, indicating its distinctiveness from the remaining species in the genus. None of its congeners present the combination of delicate codonhexasters and “ball-like” discohexasters, which confers 
<taxonomicName id="4C284D4E2E173E52A13C987EA9048D24" authority="Castello-Branco &amp; Collins &amp; Hajdu, 2020" authorityName="Castello-Branco &amp; Collins &amp; Hajdu" authorityYear="2020" box="[1310,1405,537,562]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Euplectellidae" genus="Bolosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lyssacinosida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Porifera" rank="species" species="perezi" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E173E52A13C987EA9048D24" box="[1310,1405,537,562]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">B. perezi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A26F57A42E173E52A1A49870A9A78D24" box="[1414,1502,535,562]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
obvious status as a new species. This is the 
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E173E52A7FD9827AF978D4C" bold="true" box="[991,1006,576,602]" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">fi</emphasis>
rst record of 
<taxonomicName id="4C284D4E2E173E52A0A09827A8948D4C" authorityName="Ijima" authorityYear="1904" box="[1154,1261,576,602]" class="Hexactinellida" family="Euplectellidae" genus="Bolosoma" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lyssacinosida" pageId="12" pageNumber="13" phylum="Porifera" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B95CEADF2E173E52A0A09827A8948D4C" box="[1154,1261,576,602]" italics="true" pageId="12" pageNumber="13">Bolosoma</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
for the Atlantic Ocean.
</paragraph>
